    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-08-12T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-08-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="311"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d311">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">741.53/121: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Winant</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="1" xml:id="d311fn1">The Department’s file copy of this
                        telegram is endorsed “FDR” in Roosevelt’s hand.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">u.s. urgent</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-08-12">August 12,
                            1943</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4856. Secret for the Ambassador.</p>
                <p>Your 5051, August 4, 4 p.m.<note n="2" xml:id="d311fn2">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_609">p. 609</ref>.</note> and
                    4285, June 29, 10 p.m.<note n="3" xml:id="d311fn3">See <ref
                            target="frus1943v02#pg_534">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1943, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, pp. 534</ref>–<ref
                            target="frus1943v02#pg_535">535</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>With regard to the British assurances, this Government is ready to communicate to
                    the Portuguese Government (1) its concurrence <pb facs="0727" n="613"
                        xml:id="pg_613"/> in the undertaking to withdraw troops upon the termination
                    of hostilities and (2) its agreement to respect Portuguese sovereignty in all
                    Portuguese colonies.</p>
                <p>With regard to the other conditions laid down by Dr. Salazar, our Chiefs of
                    Staff, with the President’s approval, have indicated to the British Chiefs of
                    Staff that while appreciative of the delicacy of conversations now in progress
                    between the British and the Portuguese, nevertheless any agreement restricting
                    facilities in <gloss target="#t_Bracken1">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bracken</hi>
                    </gloss> to British aircraft is unacceptable to this country and would not be in
                    harmony with the <gloss target="#t_Trident1">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Trident</hi>
                    </gloss> Agreement.<note n="4" xml:id="d311fn4">See <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>,
                            <ref target="#pg_366">p. 366</ref>.</note> They have further indicated
                    the vital importance that <gloss target="#t_Bracken1">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bracken</hi>
                    </gloss> facilities be accorded air ferry, transport and military operations for
                    this country. Obviously this would necessitate adequate protective and ground
                    maintenance personnel.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
